5.1 variable transformations

We draw two histograms to compare the distribution of original house prices and log-transformed house prices.

# Histogram of the response variable
par(mfrow=c(2,1))
hist(training_data_selected1$price, breaks=300, xlab="Price", main="")
hist(log(training_data_selected1$price), breaks=300, xlab="Log price", main="")

From the comparison of histograms, logarithmic transformation seems to be an effective step. Logarithmic transformation changes the price distribution from a right-skewed distribution to look closer to a normal distribution, which can improve the fitting and prediction capabilities of the regression model.

Observation leads to the following conclusions: The range of residuals, with the median being very close to 0, indicates that the model’s predictions are relatively close to the actual values. For the coefficients, most of the independent variables are significant. Regarding model fit: The adjusted R-squared value is 0.5389, which suggests that the model explains 53.89% of the variance in price. This is a relatively high value, indicating a good fit of the model. The F-statistic is very large, and the p-value is extremely small, further confirming that at least one predictor variable is effective in the model. Multicollinearity: Based on the provided variance inflation factor (VIF) values, all are below 5, suggesting that the multicollinearity among the predictor variables in the model is acceptable. In summary, the model significantly improved in fitting after the logarithmic transformation, and there are no evident multicollinearity issues. Therefore, it can be considered that the model has been improved.

The Scale-Location plot’s distribution appears uniform, indicating that the log transformation may have successfully stabilized the variance of the residuals. actual_vs_predicted <- function(input, actual_col, pred_col) {
  df <- input
  df <- df[order(df[[actual_col]]),]
  df$bin <- cut(df[[actual_col]], breaks = quantile(df[[actual_col]], probs = seq(0, 1, by = 0.1), na.rm = TRUE), include.lowest = TRUE, labels = FALSE)

  grouped <- aggregate(cbind(df[[actual_col]], df[[pred_col]]), by = list(df$bin), FUN = mean)
  colnames(grouped) <- c('bin', actual_col, pred_col)

  plot(grouped[[actual_col]], type = 'l', col = 'blue', xlab = 'Bin', ylab = 'Values', main = 'Actual vs Predicted')
  lines(grouped[[pred_col]], col = 'red')
  legend("topright", legend = c('Actual', 'Predicted'), col = c('blue', 'red'), lty = 1)
  xlim <- c(1, length(unique(df$bin)))
  ylim <- range(c(grouped[[actual_col]], grouped[[pred_col]]))
  axis(1, at = seq(xlim[1], xlim[2], by = 1), labels = levels(df$bin), las = 2)
  axis(2, at = seq(ylim[1], ylim[2], by = 10))
  
  grouped['% diff'] <- (grouped[[pred_col]] / grouped[[actual_col]] - 1) * 100
  result_df <- grouped

  return(result_df)
}
